# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bicellum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bicellum/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:bicellum/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:bicellum/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:bicellum/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:bicellum/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:bicellum/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:bicellum/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Algospongia (vernacular name: algosponges) is a taxon of calcified fossil organisms comprising around 90 accepted genera and several hundred species, treated taxonomically as a single class in an unspecified phylum.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Originally considered to be fossil sponges or "pseudo algae", an assignment now refuted, their taxonomic position is somewhat unresolved.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Of the three most prominent recent researchers, B.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Mamet (Belgium) assigns certain families (e.g.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Palaeoberesellaceae, Beresellaceae and Issinellaceae) to Chlorophyta (green algae) as an order of that phylum (Palaeosiphonocladales), at least one other family (Ungdarellaceae) to Rhodophyta (red algae), and some other genera (*Groenlandella*, *Labyrinthoconus*) simply to "Microproblematica".
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Cózar (Spain) treated Algospongia (such as the family Calcifoliaceae) as Algae *incertae sedis*, before deciding (in 2010) against any algal affinity and reassigning them to the [zoological] protists, as a group possibly paralleling the Foraminifera.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Since that paper, Cózar has continued to use zoological terminology in his published works, while Vachard has once again assigned the group to the Algae *incertae sedis*, lying hypothetically mid-way between the extant Rhodophyta and Chlorophyta.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] A number of the genera allocated to Algospongia in the present treatment (which follows Vachard & Cózar, 2010 in the main) were recently (2021) treated as either Foraminifera, or as red or green algae, in the World Register of Marine Species, a situation that is currently under revision.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Members of the group occur in the fossil record from the Ordovician to the Late Permian periods, although only *Wetheredella* is prominent prior to the start of the Devonian.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] Algosponges are described as a group of sessile or attached microorganisms with characteristic calcified walls described as "yellowish, apparently granular" that are frequently perforated, and possess either lateral or terminal apertures between successive chambers or cells.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] The treatment below is based on that published by Vachard & Cózar in 2010, (alternative, botanical treatment indicated separated by "/"); more recent genera (post 2010) and, in some cases, corrections have been added per other available sources.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] The possibly analogous Foraminifera (protists or Protozoa in many classifications) are members of the clade SAR, which is presently assigned to the kingdom Chromista in many classifications.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] The stratigraphic range of selected algosponge genera is summarised in Figure 15 of Vachard & Cózar (2010).
[src:bicellum/algospongia] From this Figure it is apparent that *Wetheredella* is the sole representative of the group from the Upper Ordovician through the Silurian, being joined by *Asphaltinoides* a little before the Silurian ends.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] The majority of other genera then develop within, and/or are restricted to, the Devonian through Carboniferous periods, with a relatively small number (16) persisting through the Permian before all becoming extinct by the end of that period.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] The same authors also comment (their "Conclusion" no.
[src:bicellum/algospongia] As mentioned above, members of the claimed single class Algospongia have been assigned to different taxonomic groups over time, with no clear consensus emerging.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The **alveolates** are a group of protists, considered a major clade or superphylum within Eukaryota.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] They are currently grouped with the Stramenopiles and Rhizaria among the protists with tubulocristate mitochondria into the SAR supergroup.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The most notable shared characteristic is the presence of cortical (near the surface) alveoli (sacs).
[src:bicellum/alveolate] These are flattened vesicles (sacs) arranged as a layer just under the membrane and supporting it, typically contributing to a flexible pellicle (thin skin).
[src:bicellum/alveolate] In armored dinoflagellates they may contain stiff plates.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Alveolates have mitochondria with tubular cristae (invaginations), and cells often have pore-like intrusions through the cell surface.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The group contains free-living and parasitic organisms, predatory flagellates, and photosynthetic organisms.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Almost all sequenced mitochondrial genomes of ciliates and apicomplexa are linear.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The mitochondria almost all carry mtDNA of their own but with greatly reduced genome sizes.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Exceptions are *Cryptosporidium* which are left with only a mitosome, the circular mitochondrial genomes of *Acavomonas* and *Babesia microti*, and *Toxoplasma*'s highly fragmented mitochondrial genome, consisting of 21 sequence blocks which recombine to produce longer segments.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The relationship of apicomplexa, dinoflagellates and ciliates had been suggested during the 1980s, and this was confirmed in the early 1990s by comparisons of ribosomal RNA sequences, most notably by Gajadhar *et al*.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith introduced the formal name Alveolata in 1991, although at the time he considered the grouping to be a paraphyletic assemblage.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Many biologists prefer the use of the colloquial name 'alveolate'.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Alveolata include around six major groups.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The Acavomonidia and Colponemidia were previously grouped together as colponemids, a taxon now split because each has a distinctive organization or ultrastructural identity.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The Acavomonidia are closer to the dinoflagellate/perkinsid group than the Colponemidia are.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] As such, the informal term "colponemids", as it stands currently, covers two non-sister groups within Alveolata: the Acavomonidia and the Colponemidia.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] As of present, five genera of colponemids are recognized.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The Apicomplexa and dinoflagellates may be more closely related to each other than to the ciliates.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Both have plastids, and most share a bundle or cone of microtubules at the top of the cell.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] In apicomplexans this forms part of a complex used to enter host cells, while in some colorless dinoflagellates it forms a peduncle used to ingest prey.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Various other genera are closely related to these two groups, mostly flagellates with a similar apical structure.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] These include free-living members in *Oxyrrhis* and *Colponema*, and parasites in *Perkinsus*, *Parvilucifera*, *Rastrimonas* and the ellobiopsids.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] In 2001, direct amplification of the rRNA gene in marine picoplankton samples revealed the presence of two novel alveolate lineages, called group I and II.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Group I has no cultivated relatives, while group II is related to the dinoflagellate parasite *Amoebophrya*, which was classified until now in the Syndiniales dinoflagellate order.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Some studies suggested the haplosporids, mostly parasites of marine invertebrates, might belong here, but they lack alveoli and are now placed among the Cercozoa.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The ellobiopsids are of uncertain relation within the alveolates.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Silberman et al 2004 establish that the *Thalassomyces* genus of ellobiopsids are alveolates using phylogenetic analysis, however as of 2016 no more certainty exists on their place.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The development of plastids among the alveolates is intriguing.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith proposed the alveolates developed from a chloroplast-containing ancestor, which also gave rise to the Chromista (the chromalveolate hypothesis).
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Other researchers have speculated that the alveolates originally lacked plastids and possibly the dinoflagellates and Apicomplexa acquired them separately.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] However, it now appears that the alveolates, the dinoflagellates, the Colpodellida and the heterokont algae acquired their plastids from a red alga with evidence of a common origin of this organelle in all these four clades.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] A Bayesian estimate places the evolution of the alveolate group at ~850 million years ago.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The Alveolata consist of Myzozoa, ciliates, and colponemids.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] In other words, the term Myzozoa, meaning "to siphon the contents from prey", may be applied informally to the common ancestor of the subset of alveolates that are neither ciliates nor colponemids.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Predation upon algae is an important driver in alveolate evolution, as it can provide sources for endosymbiosis of novel plastids.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The term Myzozoa is therefore a handy concept for tracking the history of the alveolate group.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The ancestors of the alveolate group may have been photosynthetic.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] The ancestral alveolate probably possessed a plastid.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Chromerids, apicomplexans, and peridinin dinoflagellates have retained this organelle.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] In one school of thought the common ancestor of the dinoflagellates, apicomplexans, *Colpodella*, Colpodellida, and *Voromonas* was a myzocytotic predator with two heterodynamic flagella, micropores, trichocysts, rhoptries, micronemes, a polar ring and a coiled open sided conoid.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] While the common ancestor of alveolates may also have possessed some of these characteristics, it has been argued that Myzocytosis was not one of these characteristics, as ciliates ingest prey by a different mechanism.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] An ongoing debate concerns the number of membranes surrounding the plastid across apicomplexans and certain dinoflagellates, and the origin of these membranes.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] This ultrastructural character can be used to group organisms and if the character is in common, it can imply that phyla had a common photosynthetic ancestor.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Ciliates are a model alveolate, having been genetically studied in great depth over the longest period of any alveolate lineage.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] They are unusual among eukaryotes in that reproduction involves a micronucleus and a macronucleus.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Their reproduction is easily studied in the lab, and made them a model eukaryote historically.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Being entirely predatory and lacking any remnant plastid, their development as a phylum illustrates how predation and autotrophy are in dynamic balance and that the balance can swing one way or other at the point of origin of a new phylum from mixotrophic ancestors, causing one ability to be lost.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Few algae have been studied for epigenetics.
[src:bicellum/alveolate] Those for which epigenetic data are available include some algal alveolates.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Some are only 10–20 μm in diameter, while others are among the largest protozoa.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The well-known species *Amoeba proteus,* which may reach 800 μm in length, is often studied in schools and laboratories as a representative cell or model organism, partly because of its convenient size.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Multinucleate amoebae like *Chaos* and *Pelomyxa* may be several millimetres in length, and some multicellular amoebozoa, such as the "dog vomit" slime mold *Fuligo septica*, can cover an area of several square meters.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Amoebozoa is a large and diverse group, but certain features are common to many of its members.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The amoebozoan cell is typically divided into a granular central mass, called endoplasm, and a clear outer layer, called ectoplasm.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] During locomotion, the endoplasm flows forwards and the ectoplasm runs backwards along the outside of the cell.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In motion, many amoebozoans have a clearly defined anterior and posterior and may assume a "monopodial" form, with the entire cell functioning as a single pseudopod.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Large pseudopods may produce numerous clear projections called subpseudopodia (or determinate pseudopodia), which are extended to a certain length and then retracted, either for the purpose of locomotion or food intake.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] A cell may also form multiple indeterminate pseudopodia, through which the entire contents of the cell flow in the direction of locomotion.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] These are more or less tubular and are mostly filled with granular endoplasm.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The cell mass flows into a leading pseudopod, and the others ultimately retract, unless the organism changes direction.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] While most amoebozoans are "naked," like the familiar *Amoeba* and *Chaos*, or covered with a loose coat of minute scales, like *Cochliopodium* and *Korotnevella*, members of the order Arcellinida form rigid shells, or tests, equipped with a single aperture through which the pseudopods emerge.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In all amoebozoa, the primary mode of nutrition is phagocytosis, in which the cell surrounds potential food particles with its pseudopods, sealing them into vacuoles within which they may be digested and absorbed.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Some amoebozoans have a posterior bulb called a uroid, which may serve to accumulate waste, periodically detaching from the rest of the cell.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] When food is scarce, most species can form cysts, which may be carried aerially and introduce them to new environments.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In slime moulds, these structures are called spores, and form on stalked structures called fruiting bodies or sporangia.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Mixotrophic species living in a symbiotic relationship with microalgae of the genus Chlorella, which lives inside the cytoplasm of their host, have been found in Arcellinida and *Mayorella*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The majority of Amoebozoa lack flagella and more generally do not form microtubule-supported structures except during mitosis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] However, flagella do occur among the Archamoebae, and many slime moulds produce biflagellate gametes .
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The flagellum is generally anchored by a cone of microtubules, suggesting a close relationship to the opisthokonts.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The mitochondria in amoebozoan cells characteristically have branching tubular cristae.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] However, among the Archamoebae, which are adapted to anoxic or microaerophilic habitats, mitochondria have been lost.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Strong similarities between Amoebozoa and Opisthokonts lead to the hypothesis that they form a distinct clade.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In their Revised Classification of Eukaryotes (2012), Adl et al. proposed Amorphea as a more suitable name for a clade of approximately the same composition, a sister group to the Diaphoretickes.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] More recent work places the members of Amorphea together with the malawimonids and collodictyonids in a proposed clade called Opimoda, which comprises one of two major lineages diverging at the root of the eukaryote tree of life, the other being Diphoda.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Traditionally all amoebozoa with lobose pseudopods were grouped together in the class Lobosea, placed with other amoeboids in the phylum Sarcodina or Rhizopoda, but these were considered to be unnatural groups.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Structural and genetic studies identified the percolozoans and several archamoebae as independent groups.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In phylogenies based on rRNA their representatives were separate from other amoebae, and appeared to diverge near the base of eukaryotic evolution, as did most slime molds.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] However, revised trees by Cavalier-Smith and Chao in 1996 suggested that the remaining lobosans do form a monophyletic group, to which the Archamoebae and Mycetozoa were closely related, although the percolozoans were not.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Subsequently, they emended the phylum Amoebozoa to include both the subphylum Lobosa and a new subphylum Conosa, comprising the Archamoebae and the Mycetozoa.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Recent molecular genetic data appear to support this primary division of the Amoebozoa into Lobosa and Conosa.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The former, as defined by Cavalier-Smith and his collaborators, consists largely of the classic Lobosea: non-flagellated amoebae with blunt, lobose pseudopods (*Amoeba*, *Acanthamoeba, Arcella, Difflugia etc.*).
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The latter is made up of both amoeboid and flagellated cells, characteristically with more pointed or slightly branching subpseudopodia (Archamoebae and the Mycetozoan slime molds).
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] From older studies by Cavalier-Smith, Chao & Lewis 2016 and Silar 2016.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Also recent phylogeny indicates the Lobosa are paraphyletic: Conosa is sister of the Cutosea.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Vase-shaped microfossils (VSMs) discovered around the world show that amoebozoans have existed since the Neoproterozoic Era.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The fossil species *Melanocyrillium hexodiadema*, *Palaeoarcella athanata*, and *Hemisphaeriella ornata* come from rocks 750 million years old.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] All three VSMs share a hemispherical shape, invaginated aperture, and regular indentations, that strongly resemble modern arcellinids, which are shell-bearing amoebozoans belonging to the class Tubulinea.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] *P. athanata* in particular looks the same as the extant genus *Arcella*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The recently available *Acanthamoeba* genome sequence revealed several orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] This finding suggests that *Acanthamoeba* is capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In sexually reproducing eukaryotes, homologous recombination (HR) ordinarily occurs during meiosis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The meiosis-specific recombinase, Dmc1, is required for efficient meiotic HR, and Dmc1 is expressed in *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The purified Dmc1 from *E. histolytica* forms presynaptic filaments and catalyzes ATP-dependent homologous DNA pairing and DNA strand exchange over at least several thousand base pairs.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The DNA pairing and strand exchange reactions are enhanced by the eukaryotic meiosis-specific recombination accessory factor (heterodimer) Hop2-Mnd1.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] These processes are central to meiotic recombination, suggesting that *E. histolytica* undergoes meiosis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Studies of *Entamoeba invadens* found that, during the conversion from the tetraploid uninucleate trophozoite to the tetranucleate cyst, homologous recombination is enhanced.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Expression of genes with functions related to the major steps of meiotic recombination also increased during encystations.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] These findings in *E. invadens*, combined with evidence from studies of *E. histolytica* indicate the presence of meiosis in the *Entamoeba*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] A comparative genetic analysis indicated that meiotic processes are present in all major amoebozoan lineages.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Since *Amoebozoa* diverged early from the eukaryotic family tree, these results also suggest that meiosis was present early in eukaryotic evolution.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis, also known as amebiasis or entamoebiasis, is an infection caused by any of the amoebozoans of the *Entamoeba* group.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Symptoms are most common upon infection by *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis can present with no, mild, or severe symptoms.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Symptoms may include abdominal pain, mild diarrhoea, bloody diarrhea or severe colitis with tissue death and perforation.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] This last complication may cause peritonitis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] People affected may develop anemia due to loss of blood.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Invasion of the intestinal lining causes amoebic bloody diarrhea or amoebic colitis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] If the parasite reaches the bloodstream it can spread through the body, most frequently ending up in the liver where it causes amoebic liver abscesses.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Liver abscesses can occur without previous diarrhea.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Cysts of *Entamoeba* can survive for up to a month in soil or for up to 45 minutes under fingernails.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] It is important to differentiate between amoebiasis and bacterial colitis.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The preferred diagnostic method is through faecal examination under microscope, but requires a skilled microscopist and may not be reliable when excluding infection.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] This method however may not be able to separate between specific types.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Increased white blood cell count is present in severe cases, but not in mild ones.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The most accurate test is for antibodies in the blood, but it may remain positive following treatment.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Prevention of amoebiasis is by separating food and water from faeces and by proper sanitation measures.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] There are two treatment options depending on the location of the infection.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis in tissues is treated with either metronidazole, tinidazole, nitazoxanide, dehydroemetine or chloroquine, while luminal infection is treated with diloxanide furoate or iodoquinoline.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] For treatment to be effective against all stages of the amoeba may require a combination of medications.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Infections without symptoms do not require treatment but infected individuals can spread the parasite to others and treatment can be considered.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Treatment of other *Entamoeba* infections apart from *E. histolytica* is not needed.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis is present all over the world.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] About 480 million people are infected with what appears to be *E. histolytica* and these result in the death of between 40,000–110,000 people every year.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Most infections are now ascribed to *E. dispar*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] *E. dispar* is more common in certain areas and symptomatic cases may be fewer than previously reported.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The first case of amoebiasis was documented in 1875 and in 1891 the disease was described in detail, resulting in the terms *amoebic dysentery* and *amoebic liver abscess*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] Further evidence from the Philippines in 1913 found that upon ingesting cysts of *E. histolytica* volunteers developed the disease.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] It has been known since 1897 that at least one non-disease-causing species of *Entamoeba* existed (*Entamoeba coli*), but it was first formally recognized by the WHO in 1997 that *E. histolytica* was two species, despite this having first been proposed in 1925.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] In addition to the now-recognized *E. dispar* evidence shows there are at least two other species of *Entamoeba* that look the same in humans - *E. moshkovskii* and *Entamoeba bangladeshi*.
[src:bicellum/amoebozoa] The reason these species haven't been differentiated until recently is because of the reliance on appearance.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The International Society of Protistologists, the recognised body for taxonomy of protozoa, recommended in 2012 that the term Unikont be changed to Amorphea because the name "Unikont" is based on a hypothesized synapomorphy that the ISOP authors and other scientists later rejected.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] It includes amoebozoa, opisthokonts, and apusomonads.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Thomas Cavalier-Smith proposed a new phylum: Sulcozoa, which consists of the subphyla Apusozoa (Apusomonadida and Breviatea), and Varisulca, which includes the taxa Diphyllatea, Discocelida, Mantamonadida, Planomonadida and Rigifilida.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Further work by Cavalier-Smith showed that Sulcozoa is paraphyletic.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Apusozoa also appears to be paraphyletic.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Varisulca has been redefined to include planomonads, *Mantamonas* and *Collodictyon*.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] A new taxon has been created - Glissodiscea - for the planomonads and *Mantamonas*.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Again, the validity of this revised taxonomy awaits confirmation.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Amoebozoa seems to be monophyletic with two major branches: Conosa and Lobosa.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Conosa is divided into the aerobic infraphylum Semiconosia (Mycetozoa and Variosea) and secondarily anaerobic Archamoebae.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Lobosa consists entirely of non-flagellated lobose amoebae and has been divided into two classes: Discosea, which have flattened cells, and Tubulinea, which has predominantly tube-shaped pseudopodia.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The group includes eukaryotic cells that, for the most part, have a single emergent flagellum, or are amoebae with no flagella.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The unikonts include opisthokonts (animals, fungi, and related forms) and Amoebozoa.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] By contrast, other well-known eukaryotic groups, which more often have two emergent flagella (although there are many exceptions), are often referred to as bikonts.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Bikonts include Archaeplastida (plants and relatives) and SAR supergroup, the Cryptista, Haptista, Telonemia and Picozoa.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The unikonts have a triple-gene fusion that is lacking in the bikonts.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] The three genes that are fused together in the unikonts, but not bacteria or bikonts, encode enzymes for synthesis of the pyrimidine nucleotides: carbamoyl phosphate synthase, dihydroorotase and aspartate carbamoyltransferase.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] This must have involved a double fusion, a rare pair of events, supporting the shared ancestry of Opisthokonta and Amoebozoa.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] Cavalier-Smith originally proposed that unikonts ancestrally had a single flagellum and single basal body.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] This is unlikely, however, as flagellated opisthokonts, as well as some flagellated Amoebozoa, including *Breviata*, actually have two basal bodies, as in typical 'bikonts' (even though only one is flagellated in most unikonts).
[src:bicellum/amorphea] This paired arrangement can also be seen in the organization of centrioles in typical animal cells.
[src:bicellum/amorphea] In spite of the name of the group, the common ancestor of all 'unikonts' was probably a cell with two basal bodies.
